(630, 50, '2023-05-13 17:42:53', '2023-05-13 21:42:53', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On Wednesday, May 10th, 2023, Club Running saw the return of the Ice Cream Trifecta Run. It is a challenge of speed, endurance, grit, strength, intellect, humor, dedication, wit, balance, agility, and most importantly, consumption.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Beginning at SPH, competitors run to the Maryland Dairy at Stamp, then down to Cold Stone Creamery on South Campus, then up Route 1 to Rita’s, and then back to SPH for the finish. At each stop, competitors must purchase a small ice cream (custard at Rita’s) and consume it completely before leaving for the next stop.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The following recap is based on eyewitness recounts and some Strava posts. Please forward all corrections to my secretary Andrew Cullen and I might fix it (but probably not).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>SPH to Maryland Dairy</strong>&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>12 official competitors (and some other ice cream enthusiast spectators) toed the line at SPH. The lead pack booked it for Stamp by cutting through the Cambridge Community area and up to Stamp. Leading the pack to the Maryland Dairy were Eamon Plante, Jacob Bush, and Ian Siegler, and Andrew Cullen (for about 30 seconds). Onlookers looked on in horror as the line for the Maryland Dairy began to form to unprecedented lengths seen outside of Student tour groups.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When I finally made it to Maryland Dairy, Jacob and Eamon were already inhaling their ice creams. I asked Jacob for a comment about how he felt at the current time and he replied, “feeling fire.”&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Despite not being in the front pack of the line, Zach shoveled that Terpresso down and was the first competitor to leave for Cold Stone. Jacob quickly finished his strawberry ice cream to lead the chase after Zach. Cap was the next competitor to leave Maryland Dairy, followed by Eamon, then Ian and Ben.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Maryland Dairy to Cold Stone</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jacob led the chase pack after Zach en route to Cold Stone, followed by Cap, Eamon, Ian, and Ben. While Zach definitely ate faster, Jacob had the superior footspeed, passing him on the stretch across Mckeldin Mall to Cold Stone.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;Zach however managed to outkick Jacob to Cold Stone and got served first. Cold Stone is infamous for being rather slow and today was no exception. This was a key moment that secured Zach’s position in first. He demolished his ice cream before Jacob’s order even finished ringing up and booked it up Route 1 to Rita’s.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Cold Stone to Rita’s&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Zach was the first to arrive at Rita’s and ordered a custard swirl, which in retrospect he regrets and would have gone with just chocolate. Jacob arrived shortly after and had finished eating by the time Eamon, Ian, and Ben arrived.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ben was struggling with his Rita’s custard and ended up dry heaving for a bit which almost made Eamon throw up (he did not). Eamon left with a comfortable lead to finish 3rd overall. Ian demolished his Rita’s for an impressive 4th place.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The next two finishers were Ben and Cap for 5th and 6th. Cap claimed that non-competitor Sam Fields cost him time at the Rita’s by ordering in front of him and thus slowing him down. Given the gap between him and Ben was less than 12 seconds, he was probably not wrong.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Andrew “having fun with the sport” Cullen finished in 7th place about 10 minutes later, clearly having enjoyed the experience from start to finish.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Rita’s custard proved to be a killer for many competitors. The deceptively large “small” custard portion was demoralizing for many. Sohan struggled for a while with his custard, “Nate sucks. I regret ever meeting Nate.” Needless to say Sohan definitely took a while at the Rita’s stop. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dominick and Kalabe were trailing close behind Sohan and Andrew en route to Rita’s. Despite this gap, they managed to pass Sohan with their superior eating speed and ran to a sub 1 hour performance. Mason Scott also lapped Sohan at Rita’s for 10th place.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After many minutes of struggling with his custard, Sohan made it to the finish, soon followed by Hadi.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Post Race</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Andrew and Hadi took the “actually enjoy the ice cream” philosophy and had a great time eating their different ice cream treats with good company.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“I had Brenda’s Peanut Butter Frese at Maryland Dairy, Cotton candy with chocolate chips at Cold Stone, and chocolate custard at Rita’s,” said Andrew, “ Not a crazy time, but I enjoyed all of my ice cream and got to have a great time with some wonderful friends on the club.”&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“I had to uninjure myself for this race,” said Sohan.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I asked Ben Johnson for any post race thoughts he had, “This was my first food run and it was a terrible experience. I have a lot of regrets but I’m still gonna do it next year.”&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Overall, no vomiting occurred during my spectating of this race, which I think is a win for all of the competitors.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline\">Official Results</span></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1) Zach Kiedrowski - 29:33.7<br>2) Jacob Bush - 30:47.01<br>3) Eamon Plante - 37:41.47<br>4) Ian Siegler - 38:47.18<br>5) Benjamin Johnson - 41:00.88<br>6) Lucas “Cap” LaBuff - 41:12.57<br>7) Andrew Cullen - 52:19.28<br>8) Kalabe Arefeayne - 59:19.61<br>9) Dominick Cardone 59:19.90<br>10) Mason Scott - 1:00:54.28<br>11) Sohan Ganatra - 1:03:58.38<br>12) Hadi Alzayer - 1:07:32.76&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '2023 Ice Cream Trifecta Run Recap', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '628-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-05-13 17:42:53', '2023-05-13 21:42:53', '', 628, 'http://umdclubrunning.com/blog/?p=630', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(634, 61, '2023-10-18 14:08:45', '2023-10-18 18:08:45', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Introduction</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Introducing… Sam Fields! Sam is a sophomore physics major and history minor at the University of Maryland, and has been a member of UMD Club Running since his first semester on campus, Fall 2021. Sam’s passion for physics began as a young lad, having a brilliant physics teacher at Towson high school. Since then, in his first two years of studying at UMD, he’s gained a fascination specifically for high energy physics, a subject he hopes to learn more about in the remaining years of his collegiate learning.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early Years</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While Sam is very apparently an academic weapon, his arsenal expands beyond just this and dabbles in the athletic realm as well. Since before Sam was even a thought in his parents’ minds, the universe knew that running would be in his DNA. Sam’s dad was a runner when he was in high school, so it seemed like destiny that Sam would follow in his footsteps and become a runner himself. Sam felt this calling before his age even hit double digits, beginning his racing career in elementary school, signing up for the Charm City cross country races. Despite not training for these races, Sam established himself as a genetic beast in 5th grade, placing first in the elementary school division of the Towson Turkey Trot.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Living off the high of this win at the end of his elementary school career, Sam knew he would need to take it up a notch to have similar success in middle school. Immediately upon starting middle school, Sam decided to join his middle school’s cross country and track team. This involved a rigorous practice schedule of running 4 times a week. Training consistently during his middle school years, his hard work culminated in a breathtakingly impressive season his 8th grade year, winning multiple Baltimore County races during the cross country season.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>High School Turmoil</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After this 8th grade year, Sam was yet again forced to move up to his next level of schooling. In his previous years of running, Sam was racing literal children. In high school, he would continue to race children, but children who were fully grown… and very fast. It was a big jump up from middle and elementary school. In his first year at Towson high school, Sam battled to get into the top 7 runners on his team during cross country. It was tough, but Sam being someone who is often described as “built different” managed to secure a varsity spot on the team by the end of his first season. Sam would continue to thrive and conquer the poor runners who unfortunately were placed in the same heats as him during his freshman track season as well. Everything seemed like it was going smoothly, and it was for a while. However, it was only a matter of time until the <em>Baltimore Armory Incident</em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The year is 2019. It’s a cold February night, and Sam Fields is racing a 3200m race at the Baltimore Armory. At this point in time, Sam had no idea that what was about to happen was going to change the trajectory of his running career forever. Sam was running the first few laps, feeling good, chilling. Some would even say it was a good race. Then… during the second half of the race, Sam suddenly puked on the track and his race came to an end. The fans and crowd were shocked as Sam went off the track. Who knew what would come next for him?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After this incident, Sam continued running, but he couldn’t shake the memory of what happened at the Baltimore Armory. He went into a slump that would last him until the end of high school. After two years of running times not up to his standards, Sam was burnt out by the time he graduated. The two years before Sam began college were very grim in terms of his running career.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>UMD Club Running - The Revival</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After a summer off from running, Sam was hoping to restart fresh and make a return to running upon coming on campus at the University of Maryland in Fall 2021. Sam decided to join UMD Club Running as a way to get back into running while also hoping to make new friends and form a new community during this new stage of his life. Sam quickly formed some close friends in the club, and was more motivated than ever to get back into running.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>All fall semester in 2021 Sam grinded to get back into shape. He started racing cross country again during this time. He was having lots of fun but early on into the semester he still didn’t feel fully back in shape since his pre-incident self. However, towards the end of the semester Sam decided to embark on a trip to Shelbyville Indiana with his newfound club running community to race NIRCA cross country nationals. This was the start of Sam’s true return, and the first step to finally getting him out of his slump that at this point was long overstaying its welcome. Sam put down an impressive time of 28:23 in his 8k, shattering all of his expectations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>A True Long Distance Runner - Struggle and Perseverance</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Coming off of his impressive performance at nationals, Sam started training harder than ever to try to get even faster. Once the Spring semester began, Sam started having more fun with the sport than he ever had. He started running farther and farther than ever before, even reaching runs of 20 miles or longer. His strava followers looked forward to his long runs every week, and were left in awe at his posts every single time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Knowing his base fitness was the strongest its ever been, Sam decided to try running a marathon. He didn’t sign up for a race. All Sam needed was a Saturday morning and an aid bike, courtesy of Zach Kiedrowski.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It was a rainy Saturday in May 2022. It was the day Sam was going to run a marathon. Zach asked Sam several times if he wanted to reschedule for a day with better weather. Sam committed to running and decided he would do it rain or shine. Sam started running and was feeling relatively good through 20 miles and was well on pace to run a sub 3 hour time. Little did he know what was going to happen only a few miles later. Once Sam hit the 23.5 mile mark, his body gave out. He couldn’t keep going. His dreams of running a marathon that day were done. He had to get picked up and return to his dorm.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A week after the attempted marathon incident, Sam couldn’t help but still feel angry. “How could I have gone out so fast? I should’ve known better.” He wanted to do better. He didn’t want to be known as the person who <em>attempted </em>a marathon. He wanted to get the job done. Not even a week after the failed marathon attempt, Sam already made up his mind that he was going to run the Baltimore Marathon in October 2022. This was his only chance at redemption.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After a summer filled with high mileage, long runs, fast workouts, and most of all mental strength, Sam felt ready for the Baltimore Marathon. He had two goals for the race: 1. Finish 2. Finish with a Boston Qualifying time of under 3 hours. Sam was more confident than ever that he could achieve these goals. His training had gone super well, and this time he wasn’t alone. He was running the marathon along with three of his best friends and roommates.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the day of the race Sam proved that his confidence was justified. He had a hard fought race. He even yakked several times during the second half of the race, but he still finished in a Boston qualifying time of 2:52:54. Having high expectations for himself, Sam still felt like he could’ve done a bit better, but was super proud of the race, especially knowing he didn’t eat at all the whole 2 hours and 52 minutes. He knew he redeemed himself, and he was proud of himself.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Reflection and the Present Day</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sam has continued running to the present day, with lots of impressive performances since his marathon. He has put up an impressive 5k pr of 15:41, and has run cross country 8k races in under 27 minutes. Sam shows no signs of slowing down, running up to 80 miles per week and constantly improving his times.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Outside of running, Sam can be seen listening to music, with some of his favorite artists being Jimmy Hendrix and JPEGmafia. He is also an avid gamer, playing overwatch, red dead redemption, and using the two most disgusting combinations in the history of Mario Kart Wii (Funky Kong Flamerunner and Daisy Mach Bike).&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sam looks back on his running journey and is grateful. The hardships, despite feeling hopeless at times, made him so much stronger. The friendships he made are everlasting and irreplaceable. Knowing this, how could he trade his experience for anything?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Sam Fields Spotlight', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '633-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-10-18 14:08:45', '2023-10-18 18:08:45', '', 633, 'http://umdclubrunning.com/blog/?p=634', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
